air, millions canceled Disney+ and Hulu subscriptions in protest. A new campaign, \'93We Ain\'92t Buying It,\'94 sought to channel purchasing power against Trump-era policies more broadly. These efforts did not change federal law, but they signaled that civil society still had tools to impose costs on corporate and political actors. They also showed that not all economic power flowed from the top down. Money, too, could be a form of speech against the regime.\\n\\nCourts and regulators, too, offered glimpses of institutional resilience. A federal judge ordered the Justice Department to expedite Freedom of Information Act processing for Epstein-related records, and the department itself renewed a request to unseal grand jury materials, citing new congressional authorization. State supreme courts limited police misuse of Marsy\'92s Law to hide identities after shootings, even as other rulings allowed anonymity in specific cases. A federal court blocked Texas\'92s mid-decade congressional maps, forcing the state to use earlier lines while the Supreme Court reviewed the case. Environmental and health agencies continued their routine work: the EPA approved state air-quality plans, delegated landfill oversight to local authorities, and opened billions in water infrastructure financing. The FDA withdrew approval of a dangerous drug after postmarketing trials failed, convened public meetings on biosimilar fees and tobacco products, and classified new medical devices to balance safety and access. These actions did not directly move the Democracy Clock, but they preserved parts of the administrative state that still served public welfare rather than regime interest. Quiet competence still existed alongside loud abuse.\\n\\nLooking ahead from Week 45, several scheduled or pending decisions carried clear implications for democracy\'92s trajectory. The Supreme Court\'92s review of the Texas redistricting case would shape whether mid-decade gerrymanders became a standard tool for